The paper proposes a motion planner for a dynamic or partially known environment, which suggests that it could belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) or Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories. The planner integrates a database of pre-computed motion primitives, which involves optimization and cost minimization, indicating that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of random sampling and tree-based exploration suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of grid space and obstacle avoidance, which suggests that it could also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category.
